reviewText:
"Strike Back" is an imported British series that has been shown in the United States on pay cable's Cinemax.  With lots of graphic violence and gratuitous sex, the show is an amalgam of James Bond movies and TV's "24."

Michael Stonehenge (Philip Winchester), a British sergeant, and Damian Scott (Sullivan Stapleton), a former U.S. Delta Force operative who was discharged on the eve of the U.S. invasion of Iraq, are members of a top secret intelligence agency known as Section 20.  Stonehenge, Scott, and the rest of Section 20 criss-cross the globe on the trail of a deadly Middle-Eastern terror mastermind named Latif (Jimi Mistry), who is planning a major attack involving a cache of weapons of mass destruction that could have worldwide repercussions.

The series harks back to 1980's buddy-action cinema and further back still to "The Man from U.N.C.L.E."  The dialogue is often witty and far more clever than your standard action drama.  The look is slick and stylish, with episodes taking place in many exotic locales.  It's timely and relevant because the underlying dramatic thrust is tracking down terrorists bent on widespread destruction.

The six-disc Blu-ray set contains the DVD version, a Digital Copy download, and five audio commentaries with cast and crew.

By Jim Clark, publisher, Lee County Courier, Tupelo, Mississippi

Strike Back  seems like a broadcast answer to 9/11.
We are introduced to Section 20, a secret branch of the British Secret Intelligence Service.
Sergeant Michael Stonebridge (Philip Winchester) and Damian Scott (Sullivan Stapleton) are our heroes.
Stonebridge is a by-the-book Royal Marine and Special Boat Service commando. Scott (Sullivan Stapleton) is a former American Delta Force operative .
Initially Stonebridge and Scott are sent in to rescue John Porter.
Porter is a former SAS (Special Air Service). Prior to the invasion of Iraq, he was on a hostage rescue mission. During the course of the mission Porter saved the life of an Iraq child. That child goes on to kill two of Porter's soldiers. He is held responsible and chooses to retire instead of facing an unstable future.
Porter has been captured by Latif, a Pakistani terrorist, who is plotting "Project Dawn."
Stonebridge and Scott repect each other but get on each other's nerves.
"He (Scott) is the one that usually goes in first and takes the bullets, whereas Stonebridge arrives at the last minute and saves the day," Philip said.
Strike Back is based on a book of the same name from former Special Air Service (SAS) soldier turned novelist Chris Ryan. It's a believable, action packed series but hard for the layperson to follow at times.
this is a GREAT series but if you want SEASON 1 you will have to buy the all region blu-ray which has SERIES 1 & 2.  you WON'T be dissappointed.

Ahh, Cinemax. Home to all of the same movies on HBO but also home to everyone's favorite late-night soft-core porn. So how does this channel look to distinguish itself from HBO other than the soft-core porn? Two words: Original Programming. But since it's Cinemax, it has to have a program that not too  dissimilar in flavor to what Cinemax is so well-known for. So they imported a show from the UK originally called CHRIS RYAN'S STRIKE BACK, shortened the title, and according to information about that show, Cinemax splashed it with a super-sized helping of pretty graphic violence and lots of (mostly) unnecessary sex and lo and behold Cinemax gave us STRIKE BACK.

The show is, in essence, a volatile chemical mixture of the conspiracies and action of 24, the stand-alone episodic suspense and serious character work of SPOOKS (known here in the US on PBS as MI-5), the kind of tech and teamwork of THE UNIT, the kind of graphic violence Premium Cable allows for, and some of the gratuitous sex and nudity of Cinemax's late-night fare. The structure of the show is a buddy-action film with two mis-matched partners going after the bad guys and kicking (and showing) some serious buttocks, but intermingled with some more serious and shocking moments you wouldn't expect.

On the partner side you have the stiff British soldier Alex Stonebridge (the impossibly well-chiseled Philip Winchester) who is all about the orders and the mission, and then there's the sloppy and rugged American, the disgraced former Delta named Damien Scott (Sullivan Stapleton, suitably tough) who is all about the ladies and the action. Stonebrigde works for a secret unit of British Military Intelligence called Section 20, run by Colonel Eleanor Grant (a terrific Amanda Mealing). An operative of theirs is killed in the hunt to find a Middle-Eastern terror mastermind called Latif, and in order to find Latif, Scott is reluctantly brought on-board in Section 20. Over the ten episodes of this season, there are some real highlights, some real low-lights, but mostly a pretty solid piece of entertainment.

Among the real highlights of the season are an extremely tense two-parter where Stonebridge and Scott along with Capt. Kate Marshall (the lovely Eva Birthistle), another Section 20 agent and Stonebridge's secret lover, square off against a former IRA bomber (the always great Liam Cunningham); another extremely tense two-parter with Stonebridge and Scott as they partner up with an arms dealer (GAME OF THRONES's Iain Glen) to free his daughter from an African rebel army's leader (LOST's Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje); a truly magnificent set-piece involving a minefield, and a massive firefight with Stonebridge and Scott vs dozens of Chechen rebels all look to raise your pulse or stall your breathing. The final sacrifice. These are all moments that push this show into pretty awesome territory.

Among the low-lights of the show, one is that there is very little character development beyond what's on the surface. Stonebridge and Scott get by on their looks, action-hero personas and charm. The other semi-major characters of Section 20, like Maj. Sinclair (Rhashan Stone) and Sgt.  Richmond (Michelle Lukes) have no development. They're not quite red-shirt "Star Trek" characters (but to be fair, there are more than a few of those), but they have no real life to them, and that's not the fault of the performers. The only character that seems to really have a developmental arc is Col. Grant, and she has some questionable motives. Scott's sexual liasons are as unrealistic as the other Cinemax late-night fare (the woman in the bar he talks to for 2 minutes; the only beautiful hostage; etc.). The absolute worst thing the show does is a pretty significant death for Stonebridge happens, and once it's done with, it's done with. You never really see that revisit his character, and you never see anyone else grieve or really even acknowledge the death. The direction never seems terribly inspired either. It's pretty much a point-and-shoot show.

So yes, there is a first season that was shown in the UK that actually concentrates on the character who is the lynchpin of Scott coming to Section 20, but there is no way of really seeing that in the US because of the apparent region coding issues on those discs. The real showrunner of STRIKE BACK is Andy Harries, who's been doing TV and film in the UK for a few decades, with shows like WALLANDER and films like THE QUEEN. But when the show got stateside, the biggest name involved was Frank Spotnitz, whose work previously included the awful remake of KOLCHAK: THE NIGHT STALKER for TV a few years back and sci-fi thrillers like HARSH REALM and MILLENIUM. But Spotnitz was also a producer for THE X-FILES (and the first episode of this show has a HUGE shout-out to that show) so having someone on staff who was a big part of one of the greatest television series ever is a big plus in this show's favor.

STRIKE BACK is a throwback to charming 80's buddy-action cinema but with the sensibilites of more modern storytelling techniques, and a healthy amount of flesh give this show a very unusual flavor, but it's tasty enough to make you want seconds.

Strike Back season 2 have a good story, and good cinematography with believeable photography. Its shortcomings are the lack of memorable characters, something season 1 had, especially with Richard Armitage's character, John Porter. Also I find the amount of violence shown exceeding my preference. If you expect the same quality in all aspects as season 1, you will probably be disappointed. But if you expect it to be something on its own, rather than a regular follow-up season, then you can find liking season 2 easier. Here is season 1 on BD: Chris Ryan's Strike Back (Blu-ray Disc)

24 off the air! The Border off the air! Spooks in the final season! Caught Strike Back on Cinemax and it is great to watch a series with a budget that is not hampered by US censors. Violence galore, nudity and a very interesting plot. Strike Back may not have the complexity of Spooks, though with much more in your face violence, it is like 24 on steroids with some of the witty dialogue reminiscent of the last 2 seasons of The Border. As this is done in a serial format, watching in a few sittings would be like a really long non stop action movie. Highly recommended.

Wasn't sure this reboot for tv could stand against the original movies, but it more than does. Martin Riggs has WAY more depth and screen chemistry, especially with Jordana Brewster as his therapist/friend/colleague,  than Mel Gibson ever did.  I do WISH the makeup department would do something with his hair. He's supposed to be the hottie, but his unkempt appearance comes off as staged.

Everyone's acting is impeccable, and the scripts for each episode are gritty and believable.  This series more than stands on its own, and we can look forward to future seasons.

There are a lot of good things about this  show. It's well done overall and in some ways has a more realistic feel too it. Good people get hurt and die, bad people sometimes win. Fights are chaotic and brutal. I'm sure real life military would cringe at some the the action, and it is admittedly a little over-the-top. But it's still fun and well done; similar to a James Bond movie.  The plot, while somewhat unrealistic, is good enough to keep me going. The problem here is that there is so much unnecessary sex. I wouldn't complain if it was occasional or necessary to the plot. But it's not either of those. Literally every episode has at least one, if not more sex/nude scenes. If that's what your watching for, then great. But for those of us who want a decent action show without the filth of unnecessary soft-porn, this is not for us.

Let's see if I understand today's action thrillers. Men's dress: fatigues or tight jeans. Men's body: muscular with square jaw and habitual two day growth of facial hair.  In addition, butt should be muscular and as round as a man's butt can get because we'll be see a lot of it.  For the women: tight pants, tank tops or button up blouse that is a size too small and a push up bra. Since we'll be seeing a lot of their chests during each and every episode, nice boobs are a must along with an appropriate butt.  The good guys are usually made up of: ex or active military, M5, ex-SWAT of a mixture of these types.  There is usually an angry guy that doesn't like to follow the rules and for some reason can boink any female that he comes within 5 feet of.  Even the enemy women.  I'm sure there must be a minimum number of bullets expended during every gun battle and blood has to be splattered during every gun fight.  Although hand to hand combat occurs with regularity, our heroes heal quickly and by the next episode show no signs of any damage. I'm afraid that the women in this series (as well as a couple of others I've watched) usually aren't as smart or deadly as their-male counterparts but do seem to hold a lot of command positions.  Since I am not a long-time watcher of action movies, I may have missed the good points that other reviewers have mentioned.  It seems to me, though, that if I can figure out the plots before we reach the end of the episode and know who's going to make it to the next show, that there is something lacking in the story line and script writing.  I won't even go into the acting. There is not much of it required.  The language is what you would expect.  One wonders how James Bond made it through his continuing adventures with out saying the "F" word or making enough enough noise during sex to wake the dead.  I will continue to try an action film now and again because I want to learn about this type of movie. I'm afraid I can't recommend this one to you.

This is what you get when you pay actors in empty cartridge cases.  The fire fights sound like secretarial classes in full typing test mode.  Contrary to movie makers' beliefs, bullets from AK 47 rifles do not weave random patterns in the air.  They go where the sights line up.  And the soul searching constantly wrestles for screen time with the topless interludes and the noisy sex bouts.
There is a saying: "The best laid plans of mice and men oft go awry."  That doesn't apply here. All the plans are bad.  Every operation by "Team 20" is a house of cards that collapses at the creak of a floorboard.
A lot of effort went into the mechanics of this series.  People in all the crafts worked their butts off making it.  If you feel charitable, you could decide to treat it as a parody and milk it for the unintended laughs.  There's plenty of nudity and coarse language, so don't let the little kiddies watch unless you want them to grow up strange.

They must have had a UK director cuz this show doesn't have the "American type" of director created feel to it like every American action show has. And they battle terror in Thailand, Beirut, Paris, etc. Basically places that American produced shows don't. Stonebridge is the Brit who's married and the American is the womanizer who has a sense of humor he eventually rubs off on his Brit counter part.

Each episode is very exciting (I've watched 1-4 a couple times already) with the good guys trying to stop the bad guys throughout the season, with the last episode being high octane, which makes you want it to never stop!

This Cinemax produced cable show its ten times better than 24 which was a hit in America but bores the heck out of me that I just couldn't watch more than five episodes concurrently!

Although the production values are high, and the locations handsome, and there are inordinate amounts of gratuitous gore and nudity, the storytelling is pretty standard and old-fashioned: two apparently indestructible hunks fight terrorism around the world, blah blah. Kind of Man From U.N.C.L.E. for the 21st century. One of the hunks is an American who does surprisingly well with a British accent. Most American actors get lost somewhere in the Keanu-in-Dracula zone. The other is an Aussie doing an American accent -- one of those generic 21st-century Aussie hunks who all look like their stage name should be Biff Kake. He, of course, is a wisecracking discipline problem, because, well, he's American. Not usually one to complain about this, but the way virtually every woman on the show is there to have sex with one or the other of them  really is demeaning and sexist and detracts from rather than adds to the edgy, gritty vibe they're aiming for.

Tiresome, droll, and completely lacking in imagination, much less any regard for what the audience really wants to see, which is a vigorous prosecution of the War on Terror, which of course means taking it to the islamic extremists who are at war with the civilized world, whether we recognize that fact or not. The show also became increasingly lazy and stupid, as you find yourself asking more and more frequently, "Now why would they do that?" I would have recommended ramping up the sex, since Cinemax is pretty much all about soft core porn, and making the show a comedy. Maybe call it something like "If Bill Clinton worked for MI6." Thus, this mess is a failed concept and a missed opportunity.

Years ago, there was an excellent tv series on British television called "The Sandbaggers," showing how the intelligence community really worked on the ground, with Orwell's "rough men" doing bad things to bad people.

Take that, ramp it up with modern technology - great ops room - and match it with smart guys using guns and explosive - lots of guns, lots of explosives - with some of the most expert stunt work in this field you will see. Now, add two guys - one, classic upper class (meritocratic) SAS/MI-6 type, and another, bit of a wild man, ex Delta Force, great with the ladies. Then, add a smart women to do the thinking - Amanda Mealing is perfect.

Mix with bad people doing bad things, and you have a masterfully directed series, one that is well worth watching.

This is based in Capetown, South Africa (great scenery!) , but they go all over the hemisphere, particularly the rougher parts of Africa, so you get a travel show, and, as this is partnered with CINEMAX, there are a lot of really good looking women.

This is an action-packed, get the bad guys, kinda show.  Two very likable heroes, who have the back and forth jabber down pat like "real" old time friends would, are perfect for the story's premise.  The story lines in each of the episodes are ones that keep you interested through out.  There are two main things that get tiring after a while:  1) the requisite sex scene in EVERY episode (I don't think it's necessary nor does it really add to the story) and 2) the extreme violence (I understand that the premise of the story is to fight terrorists, but every episode doesn't need to have 10-15 minute automatic rifle/gun battles.

The stroyline, to a certain degree, is acceptable. Much of what you get is run of mill action, analytics, etc. for this genre. I just really had a difficult time sympathizing with the protagonists or accepting the antagonists as being real. If you buy into these characters, I guess it's worth the time to sit through the episodes, but be warned...

Some of these reviewers are taking this show way too seriously. They act like it has the emotional impact of Saving Private Ryan. Really, it's just one of those B-movie type shows where they show you a bunch of action and guns, and then to keep you from getting bored, they randomly throw in sex. It doesn't have anything close to the writing quality of, say, Homeland. If you're the kind of person who likes Dolph Lundgren movies, you'll likely enjoy this show. If you have any kind of military background, you will be appalled at how inaccurate and nonsensical it is. It's one of those types of shows where the ranks and insignias are incorrect, frail women are in combat operations, and people of all ranks talk casually like buddies.
